result.execSummary:
The defendant Jacob R Ostrander was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).
  • Criminal Damage to Property, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: One year probation extension from 05/11/18 to 05/11/19

Defendant Jacob R Ostrander appeared, ADA Diane M. Donohoo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Probation Agent Laura Roller appears.  
Court notes restitution amount was $539.00 but in 2 years he has not paid a dime.  
Deft is 20 and lives with his mother in Eau Claire.  He has been trying to find a job.  Last time he worked was in January of this year in Fazoli's.  There was an incident at the house where he was living and he had to leave for a couple of weeks and he was down here for the period of time.  He was not able to get his job back at Fazoli's.  Deft says his girlfriend and mom are paying his expenses.  Agent says Dept. does not believe he has been making a good faith effort.  Atty Donohoo agrees. Statement by Mr. Ostrander.  Court notes he has not done anything to pay any restitution.  Court orders 1 year extension of probation.  9:06 am
Probation review hearing on April 17, 2018 at 08:30 am.
